-- Hong Kong shares rebound, lifted by China market
-- By Grace Li
-- Wed Sep 24, 2014 04:07AM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, Sept 24 (Reuters) - Hong Kong shares ended higher for the first time this week on Wednesday lifted by a stronger China market, with investor sentiment recovering after better-than-expected Chinese manufacturing activity.

The Hang Seng Index <.HSI> ended up 0.4 percent at 23,921.61 points. The China Enterprises Index <.HSCE> of the leading offshore Chinese listings in Hong Kong climbed 1.4 percent, snapping a four-day losing streak. Large state banks led index gains. China Construction Bank Corp <0939.HK> and Industrial and Commercial Bank of China <1398.HK> each added more than 1 percent. Chinese telcos rose after mainland media reported Apple Inc's <AAPL.O> iPhone 6 is in the final stages of review for approval, with results due shortly, quoting a top Chinese government regulator. China Telecom <0728.HK> spiked 5.2 percent. [ID:nB9N0OY00Q]